\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset

Exogenous fundamentals of the economy are functions of a shock 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}$
\end_inset

 that follows an irreducible Markov process, where 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}\in S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a finite set. We let 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{t}=\left(
s_{0},...,s_{t}\right) $
\end_inset

 denote a history of shocks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%There are $I$ types of infinitely lived agents.
\end_layout

\end_inset

There is a mass 
\begin_inset Formula $n _{i}$
\end_inset

 of a type 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 agent, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{I}n _{i}=1.$
\end_inset

 Types differ by their skills. Preferences of an agent of type 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 over stochastic processes for consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $\{c_{i,t}\}_t$
\end_inset

 and labor supply 
\begin_inset Formula $\{l_{i,t}\}_t$
\end_inset

 are ordered by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbb{E}_{0}\sum_{t=0}^{\infty } \beta^t U^{i}\left(
c_{i}(s^t),l_{i}(s^t)\right),  \label{utility lifetime}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a mathematical expectations operator conditioned on time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 information and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta \in \left( 0,1\right) $
\end_inset

 is the time discount factor. We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{i}\in \left[ 0,\bar{l}_{i}\right] $
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{l}_{i}<\infty .$
\end_inset

 Results in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Ricardian101"

\end_inset

 require no additional assumptions on 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{i}$
\end_inset

 like differentiability or convexity,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed


\begin_layout Standard
Consequently our setup allows both extensive and intensive responses of labor.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 but results in later sections do.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An agent of type 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 who supplies 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{i}$
\end_inset

 units of labor produces 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta
_{i}\left( s_t\right) l_{i}$
\end_inset

 units of output, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta _{i}(s_t)\in \Theta $
\end_inset

 is a nonnegative state-dependent scalar. Feasible allocations satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}%\label{eqn:feasiblity}
\sum_{i=1}^{I}n_{i}c_{i}(s^t)+g\left( s_{t}\right) =\sum_{i=1}^{I}\pi
_{i}\theta _{i}\left( s_{t}\right) l_{i}(s^t),  \label{feasibility goods}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left( s_{t}\right) $
\end_inset

 denotes exogenous government expenditures in state 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}.$
\end_inset

 We allow 
\begin_inset Formula $s_t$
\end_inset

 to affect government expenditures 
\begin_inset Formula $g(s_t)$
\end_inset

, and the type-specific productivities 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_i(s_t)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To save on notation, mostly we use 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t}$
\end_inset

 to denote a random variable with a time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 conditional distribution that is a function of the history 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{t}$
\end_inset

. Occasionally, we use the more explicit notion 
\begin_inset Formula $z\left(
s^{t}\right) $
\end_inset

 to denote a realization at a particular history 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{t}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%
\backslash
