\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A Ramsey planner's preferences over a vector of stochastic processes for consumption and labor supply are ordered by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbb{E}_{0}\sum_{i=1}^{I}\omega_{i}\sum_{t=0}^{\infty }\beta_t U_{t}^{i}\left( c_{i,t},l_{i,t}\right),  \label{govmt objective}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where the Pareto weights satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega _{i}\geq 0,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{I}\omega _{i}=1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In most of this paper, we study an optimal government policy when agents can trade only a one-period risk-free bond. We assume that the government imposes an affine tax. We denote proportional labor taxes by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 and lump sump transfers by 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

. With this the tax bill of an agent with wage earnings 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{i,t}\theta_{i,t}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation*}
- T_t + \tau_t \theta_{i,t}l_{i,t}. \end{equation*}
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%We allow the government to choose a feasible sequence of transfers $%
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%
\backslash
{T_{t}
\backslash
} $.
\end_layout

\end_inset

We do not restrict the sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{t}$
\end_inset

 at any 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $s^t$
\end_inset

. 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%This means that our analysis covers the following example: if
\end_layout

\end_inset

If for some type 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta _{i,t}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i, -1} = 0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U^i$
\end_inset

 is defined only on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}^2_{+}$
\end_inset

, his budget constraint will imply that the all allocations feasible for the planner have nonnegative present values of transfers, since transfers are the sole source of a type 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 agent's wealth and consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The government and agents trade a single possibly risky asset whose time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 payoff 
\begin_inset Formula $p_t$
\end_inset

 is described by an 
\begin_inset Formula $S \times S$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%
\backslash
[p_t=
\backslash
st{
\backslash
mathbb{P}(s_{t}|s_{t-1})} 
\backslash
]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[p_t=\mathbb{P}(s_{t},s_{t-1}) \]
\end_inset

We normalize the payoffs such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}_tp_{t+1}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $q_t= q_t(s^t)$
\end_inset

 be the price of the single asset at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{t}=\frac{p_t}{q_{t-1}}$
\end_inset

 be the one period returns from holding the asset from 
\begin_inset Formula $t-1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under an affine tax system, agent 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's budget constraint at 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
c_{i,t}+b_{i,t}=\left( 1-\tau _{t}\right) \theta
_{i,t}l_{i,t}+R_{t}b_{i,t-1}+T_{t},  \label{agent bc affine}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i,t}$
\end_inset

 denotes asset holdings of a type 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 agent at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t\geq 0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a gross one-period return rate from 
\begin_inset Formula $t-1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\geq 1$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{-1}\equiv 1$
\end_inset

. To rule out Ponzi schemes, we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i,t}$
\end_inset

 must be bounded from below. Except in subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Sec: extensions"

\end_inset

, we impose no further constraints on agents' borrowing and lending. Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Sec: extensions"

\end_inset

 briefly studies economies with arbitrary borrowing constraints.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The government budget constraint is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g_{t}+B_{t}=\tau _{t}\sum_{i=1}^{I}\pi _{i}\theta
_{i,t}l_{i,t}-T_{t}+R_{t}B_{t-1},  \label{govmt bc affine}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{t}$
\end_inset

 denotes the government's assets at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, which we assume are bounded from below. Our assumptions about preferences imply that the government can collect only finite revenues in each period, so this restriction rules out government-run Ponzi schemes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that private agents and the government start with assets 
\begin_inset Formula $\{b_{i,-1}\}_{i=1}^{I}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{-1}$
\end_inset

, respectively. Asset holdings satisfy the market clearing condition
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{i=1}^{I}n _{i}b_{i,t}+B_{t}=0\text{ for all }t\geq -1.
\label{feasibility bonds}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{t}$
\end_inset

 and all 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i,t}$
\end_inset

 are bounded from below, equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "feasibility bonds"

\end_inset

) implies that they are also bounded from above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Components of competitive equilibria are described below
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

