\backslash
textcolor{red}{Remark from Tom: Anmol, I agree with you very much. Also, much of this section has nothing to do with an {
\backslash
em optimal}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%equilibrium. I have done some editing to reflect this. I have written an incendiary anti Reinhart-Rogoff first paragraph to this section. }
\end_layout

\end_inset

This section sets forth a result that underlies much of this paper, namely, that the level of government debt is not a state variable for our economy. The reason is that there is an equivalence class of tax policies and asset profiles that support the same competitive equilibrium allocation. A competitive equilibrium allocation pins down only net asset positions. The assertions in this section apply to all competitive equilibria, not just the optimal ones that will be our focus in subsequent sections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%
\backslash
textcolor{blue}{Do we need a * on the initial conditions in the statement of te theorem. Previously we have used * to denote the optimal competitive equilibrium. I feel that this proof can be re-written without the *}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "theorem: main"

\end_inset

 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\left( \left \{ b_{i,-1}\right \}
_{i},B_{-1}\right) $
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left \{ \left \{ c_{i,t},l_{i,t},b_{i,t}\right \} _{i},B_{t},R_{t}\right \} _{t} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left \{ \tau _{t},T_{t}\right
\} _{t}$
\end_inset

 be a competitive equilibrium. For any bounded sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\left \{ \hat{b}_{i,t}\right \} _{i,t\geq -1}$
\end_inset

 that satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation*}
\hat{b}_{i,t}-\hat{b}_{1,t}=\tilde{b}_{i,t}\equiv b_{i,t}	-b_{1,t}\text{ for all }t\geq -1,i\geq 2,
\end{equation*}
\end_inset

there exist sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\left \{ \hat{T}_{t}\right \} _{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left \{ \hat{B}_{t}\right \} _{t\geq -1}$
\end_inset

 that satisfy (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "feasibility bonds"

\end_inset

) such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left \{ \left \{ c_{i,t},l_{i,t},\hat{b}_{i,t}\right \} _{i},\hat{B}_{t},R_{t}\right \} _{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left \{
\tau _{t},\hat{T}_{t}\right \} _{t}$
\end_inset

 constitute a competitive equilibrium given 
\begin_inset Formula $\left( \left \{ \hat{b}_{i,-1}\right \} _{i},\hat{B}_{-1}\right) $
\end_inset

. 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{T}_{t}=T_{t} + \left(\hat{b}_{1,t} - b_{1,t}\right) -
R_{t}\left(\hat{b}_{1,t-1} - b_{1,t-1}\right) \text{ for
all }t\geq 0.  \label{construct That}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

Given a tax policy 
\begin_inset Formula $\left \{ \tau _{t},\hat{T}_{t}\right \} _{t},$
\end_inset

 the allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left \{ c_{i,t},l_{i,t},\hat{b}_{i,t}\right \}_{i,t}$
\end_inset

 is a feasible choice for consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 since it satisfies
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
c_{i,t}&=&\left( 1-\tau _{t}\right) \theta _{i,t}l_{i,t}+R_{t}b_{i,t-1}-b_{i,t}+T_{t}\\
&=&\left( 1-\tau _{t}\right) \theta _{i,t}l_{i,t}+R_{t}\left( b_{i,t-1}-b_{1,t-1}\right) -\left(
b_{i,t}-b_{1,t}\right) +T_{t}+R_{t}b_{1,t-1}-b_{1,t} \\
&=&\left( 1-\tau _{t}\right) \theta _{i,t}l_{i,t}+R_{t}\left( \hat{b}_{i,t-1}-\hat{b}_{1,t-1}\right) -\left( \hat{b}_{i,t}-\hat{b}_{1,t}\right) +T_{t}+R_{t}b_{1,t-1}-b_{1,t} \\
 &=&\left( 1-\tau _{t}\right) \theta
_{i,t}l_{i,t}+R_{t}\hat{b}_{i,t-1}-\hat{b}_{i,t}+\hat{T}_{t}.
\end{eqnarray*}
\end_inset

Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left \{ c_{i,t},l_{i,t},\hat{b}_{i,t}\right \}_{i,t}$
\end_inset

 is not the optimal choice for consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, in the sense that there exists some other sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left \{ \hat{c}_{i,t},\hat{l}_{i,t},\hat{b}_{i,t}\right \}_{t}$
\end_inset

 that gives strictly higher utility. Then the choice 
\begin_inset Formula $\left \{ \hat{c}_{i,t},\hat{l}_{i,t},b_{i,t}\right \}_{t}$
\end_inset

 is feasible given the tax rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left \{ \tau _{t},T_{t}\right \} _{t}$
\end_inset

, which contradicts the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left \{ c_{i,t},l_{i,t},b_{i,t}\right \}_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the optimal choice for the consumer given taxes 
\begin_inset Formula $\left \{ \tau _{t},T_{t}\right \}
_{t}$
\end_inset

. The new allocation satisfies all other constraints and therefore is an equilibrium. 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset

An immediate corollary is that it is not total government debt but rather who owns it that affects equilibrium allocations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

