\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset

This result is closely related to Ricardian Equivalence in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "Barro1974"

\end_inset

. There are, however, some important distinctions. In Barro's representative agent model, lump sum taxes are not distortionary. In our economy, since the planner does not have person-specific taxes, a lump sum transfer introduces distortions in inequality, a force that has a significant effect on optimal policy, as we will see in following sections. Despite this, Ricardian equivalence continues to hold.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed


\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "Wallace1981"

\end_inset

's Modigliani-Miller theorem for a class of government open market operations has a similar flavor. 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "sargent1987dynamic"

\end_inset

 describes the structure of a set of related Modigliani-Miller theorems for government finance.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
