\begin_layout Standard
Representative agent models rule out Ricardian equivalence either by assuming distorting taxes or by imposing ad hoc borrowing constraints. 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%In section 
\backslash
ref{sec:Ricardian101},
\end_layout

\end_inset

By way of contrast, we have verified that Ricardian equivalence holds in our economy even though there are distorting taxes. 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
% are typically part of an optimal equilibrium.
\end_layout

\end_inset

Imposing ad-hoc borrowing limits also leaves Ricardian equivalence intact in our economy.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed


\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "Bryant1984"

\end_inset

 describe how a government can use borrowing constraints as part of a welfare-improving policy to finance exogenous government expenditures. 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "Sargent1987"

\end_inset

 describe Modigliani-Miller theorems for government finance in a collection of economies in which borrowing constraints on classes of agents produce the kind of rate of return discrepancies that Bryant and Wallace manipulate.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In economies with exogenous borrowing constraints, agents' maximization problems include the additional constraints 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
b_{i,t}\geq \underline{b}_{i}  \label{borrowing constraint}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

for some exogenously given 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \underline{b}_{i}\right\} _{i}.$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%We
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%define an equilibrium similarly to Definition 
\backslash
ref{Def: CE with affine taxes}%
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{definition}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Def: CE with affine taxes borrowing constraints"

\end_inset

For given 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(
\left \{ b_{i,-1},\underline{b}_{i}\right \} _{i},B_{-1}\right) $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left
\{ \tau _{t},T_{t}\right \} _{t},$
\end_inset

 a competitive equilibrium with affine taxes and exogenous borrowing constraints is a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\{ \left \{
c_{i,t},l_{i,t},b_{i,t}\right \} _{i},B_{t},R_{t}\}_{t} $
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left
\{ c_{i,t},l_{i,t},b_{i,t}\right \} _{i,t}$
\end_inset

 maximizes (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "utility lifetime"

\end_inset

)
\begin_inset space \space{}

\end_inset

subject to (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "agent bc affine"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "borrowing constraint"

\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $\{ b_{i,t} \}_{i,t}$
\end_inset

 are bounded, and constraints (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "feasibility goods"

\end_inset

), (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "govmt bc affine"

\end_inset

)
\begin_inset space \space{}

\end_inset

and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "feasibility bonds"

\end_inset

)
\begin_inset space \space{}

\end_inset

are satisfied. 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{definition}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can define an 
\emph on
optimal
\emph default
 competitive equilibrium with exogenous borrowing constraints by extending Definition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Def: optimal CE affine"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%The role of the initial distribution of assets  is
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%unaffected by the introduction of the ad-hoc debt limits and  so is Corollary  
\backslash
ref{corr: B does not matter}.
\end_layout

\end_inset

The introduction of the ad-hoc debt limits leaves unaltered the conclusions of Corollary 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "corr: B does not matter"

\end_inset

 and the role of the initial distribution of assets across agents. The next proposition asserts that ad-hoc borrowing limits do not limit a government's ability to respond to aggregate shocks.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed


\begin_layout Standard
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "Yared2012,Yared2013"

\end_inset

 who shows a closely related result.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{proposition}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:borrowing_constraint"

\end_inset

 Given an initial asset distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(
\left\{ b_{i,-1}\right\} _{i},B_{-1}\right)$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ c_{i,t},l_{i,t}\right\} _{i,t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ R_{t}\right\}_t $
\end_inset

 be a competitive equilibrium allocation and interest rate sequence in an economy without exogenous borrowing constraints. Then for any exogenous constraints 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \underline{b}_{i}\right\} _{i}$
\end_inset

, there is a government tax policy 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \tau _{t},T_{t}\right\} _{t}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{
c_{i,t},l_{i,t}\right\} _{i,t}$
\end_inset

 is a competitive equilibrium allocation in an economy with exogenous borrowing constraints 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(
\left\{ b_{i,-1},\underline{b}_{i}\right\} _{i},B_{-1}\right) $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{
\tau _{t},T_{t}\right\} _{t}.$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{proposition}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ c_{i,t},l_{i,t},b_{i,t}\right\} _{i,t}$
\end_inset

 be a competitive equilibrium allocation without exogenous borrowing constraints. Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta _{t}\equiv \max_{i}\left\{ \underline{b}_{i}-b_{i,t}\right\} .$
\end_inset

 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{i,t}\equiv b_{i,t}+\Delta _{t}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset space \space{}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\geq 0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{i,-1}=b_{-1}.$
\end_inset

 By Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "theorem: main"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ c_{i,t},l_{i,t},\hat{b}_{i,t}\right\} _{i,t}$
\end_inset

 is also a competitive equilibrium allocation without exogenous borrowing constraints. Moreover, by construction 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{i,t}-\underline{b}_{i}=b_{i,t}+\Delta _{t}-\underline{b}_{i}\geq 0$
\end_inset

. Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{i,t}$
\end_inset

 satisfies (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "borrowing constraint"

\end_inset

). Since agents' budget sets are smaller in the economy with exogenous borrowing constraints, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ c_{i,t},l_{i,t},\hat{b}_{i,t}\right\} _{i,t}$
\end_inset

 are feasible at interest rate process 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{
R_{t}\right\} _{t}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ c_{i,t},l_{i,t},\hat{b}_{i,t}\right\} _{i,t}$
\end_inset

 is also an optimal choice for agents in the economy with exogenous borrowing constraints 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \underline{b}_{i}\right\} _{i}.$
\end_inset

 Since all market clearing conditions are satisfied, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ c_{i,t},l_{i,t},\hat{b}_{i,t}\right\} _{i,t}$
\end_inset

 is a competitive equilibrium allocation and asset profile. 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To provide some intuition for Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:borrowing_constraint"

\end_inset

, suppose to the contrary that the exogenous borrowing constraints restricted a government's ability to achieve a desired allocation. That means that the government would want to increase its borrowing and to repay agents later, which the borrowing constraints prevent. But the government can just reduce transfers today and increase them tomorrow. That would achieve the desired allocation without violating the exogenous borrowing constraints.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Welfare can be strictly higher in an economy with exogenous borrowing constraints relative to an economy without borrowing constraints because a government might want to push some agents against their borrowing limits. When agents' borrowing constraints bind, their shadow interest rates differ from the common interest rate that unconstrained agents face. When the government rearranges tax policies to affect the interest rate, it affects constrained and unconstrained agents differently. By facilitating redistribution, this can improve welfare. 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%In the next several paragraphs, we will formalize this
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%intuition.
\end_layout

\end_inset

In appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "appndx: borrowing constraints example"

\end_inset

, we construct an example without any shocks in which the government can achieve higher welfare by using borrowing constraints to improve its ability to redistribute.
\end_layout

