\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
For 
\begin_inset Formula $I\geq 2$
\end_inset

, we can use constraint (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "affine implementability a"

\end_inset

) for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1$
\end_inset

 to eliminate 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{t}$
\end_inset

 from (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "affine implementability a"

\end_inset

) for 
\begin_inset Formula $i > 1$
\end_inset

. Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{b}_{i,t}\equiv b_{i,t}-b_{1,t}$
\end_inset

, we can represent the implementability constraints as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\label{affine implementability b} 
&&\left( c_{i,t}-c_{1,t}\right) +\tilde{b}_{i,t}\\
&=&-\frac{U_{l,t}^{i}}{U_{c,t}^{i}}l_{i,t}+\frac{U^1_{l,t}}{U^1_{c,t}}l_{1,t} +\frac{p_tU_{c,t-1}^{i}}{\beta \mathbb{E}_{t-1}p_tU_{c,t}^{i}}\tilde{b}_{i,t-1}\ \text{for\ all\ }i>1,t.  \notag
\end{eqnarray}
\end_inset

With this representation of the implementability constraints, the planner's maximization problem depends only on the 
\begin_inset Formula $I-1$
\end_inset

 variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{b}_{i,t-1}.$
\end_inset

 The reduction of the dimensionality from 
\begin_inset space \space{}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $I-1$
\end_inset

 is another consequence of theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "theorem: main"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

