\end_inset

. This condition is inherited from the restriction that only risk-free bonds are traded.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For both computational and educational purposes, it is convenient to represent the optimal policy problem recursively. For the purpose of constructing a recursive representation, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{x}= \beta^{-1}\left( U_{c}^{2}\tilde{b}_{2},...,U_{c}^{I}\tilde{b}_{I}\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\rho }=\left( U_{c}^{2}/U_{c}^{1},...,U_{c}^{I}/U_{c}^{1}\right) $
\end_inset

, and denote an allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\{c_i,l_i\}^{I}_{i=1}.$
\end_inset

 In the spirit of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "Kydland1980"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "Farhi2010"

\end_inset

, we split the Ramsey problem into a time-
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 problem that takes 
\begin_inset Formula $(\{\tilde{b}_{i,-1}\}^{I}_{i=2}, s_0)$
\end_inset

 as given and a time 
\begin_inset Formula $t \geq 1$
\end_inset

 continuation problem that takes 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm x,\bm \rho,s\_$
\end_inset

 as given. We formulate two Bellman equations and two value functions, one that pertains to 
\begin_inset Formula $t\geq 1$
\end_inset

, another to 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

. The time inconsistency of an optimal policy manifests itself in there being distinct value functions and Bellman equations at 
\begin_inset Formula $t =0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t \geq 1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

