\begin_layout Section
Characterization: Optimal allocation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In sections 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Sec: quasilinear"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Sec: more general economies"

\end_inset

 we study the long run properties of public debt and taxes. The main finding is that the levels and spreads in debt and tax rates are determined by two factors: a) the ability of the government to span aggregate shocks through the returns on the asset it trades and b)its redistributive preferences. In particular, the government accumulates debt if interest rates are lower when the its need for revenue are higher and vice versa. The long run variance of debt and taxes along with the rates of rates of convergence to the ergodic distribution are higher in economies where the magnitude of this co movement is larger. Lastly more redistributive governments issue more debt.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To study these implications, in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Sec: quasilinear"

\end_inset

 we first examine a simple economy with quasilinear preferences and i.i.d aggregate shocks. This allows us adequate tractability to formally demonstrate and clarify the main driving forces for the results mentioned above. In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Sec: more general economies"

\end_inset

 we study more general economies (in terms of heterogeneity, preferences and shocks) numerically and show that all the insights go through.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Quasilinear economy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Sec: quasilinear"

\end_inset

 We specialize the problem described in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Sec: Bellman equations"

\end_inset

 by imposing the following assumptions that are maintained throughout in this section. 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{assumption}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "ass iid"

\end_inset

 IID aggregate shocks: 
\begin_inset Formula $s_t$
\end_inset

 is i.i.d over time 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{assumption}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{assumption}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "ass quasilinear"

\end_inset

 Quasi linear preference: 
\begin_inset Formula $u(c,l)=c-\frac{l^{1+\gamma}}{1+\gamma}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{assumption}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With i.i.d shocks we can restrict our attention to payoff matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 that have identical rows denoted by the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $P(s)$
\end_inset

 with a corresponding normalization that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}P(s)=1$
\end_inset

. We collect a particular set of these vectors that are perfectly correlated with expenditure shocks 
\begin_inset Formula $g(s)$
\end_inset

 in the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}^*$
\end_inset

 defined below,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \[\mathcal{P}^*=\left\{P(s): P(s) = 1+ \frac{\beta}{ B^*}(g(s) - \mathbb{E} g) \text{ for some } B^*\in[\overline{B},\underline{B}] \right\},\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{B}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{B}$
\end_inset

 are upper and lower bounds for government assets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before characterizing the properties of Ramsey allocation for the economy with heterogeneous agents and no restrictions on transfers, we develop some results in a representative agent economy where the government 
\shape italic
cannot
\shape default
 use transfers. We later show that the allocations in this economy are obtained under certain limits on the Pareto weights for the setting with heterogeneous agents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Representative agent 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Sec: rep agent"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Environment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section describes the representative agent environment with risky debt and no transfers.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed


\begin_layout Standard
 This differs from the model studied in AMSS in two ways: first, the government trades a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

risky
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 bond instead of a risk free bond and second, the government is prohibited from using transfer where as AMSS restrict transfers to be non negative. Both of them have critical implications on the long run zero tax results that AMSS obtained. We discuss this later in the section.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Given a tax, asset policy 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\tau_t,B_t\}$
\end_inset

, the household solves, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
W_0(b_{-1})\max_{\{c_t,l_t,b_{t}\}_t}\mathbb{E}_0\sum_{t}\beta^t \left[c_t-\frac{l_t^{1+\gamma}}{1+\gamma}\right]
\end{equation}
\end_inset

subject to 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
c_t+b_{t}=(1-\tau_t)\theta l_t+R_tP_tb_{t-t}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

Using the optimality condition for labor and savings we can summarize the set of implementability constraints for the government as follows 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{rep agent QL seq implementability}
b_{t-1} \frac{P_t}{E_{t-1}P_t}=\mathbb{E}_t\sum_{j}\beta^{t+j}[c_t-l^{1+\gamma}_t] \quad \forall t
\end{equation}
\end_inset

In addition we have also have the feasibility constraint 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{feasibility}
c_t+g_t\leq\theta l_t,
\end{equation}
\end_inset

and the market clearing for bonds, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{market clearing for bonds} b_t+B_t=0.\end{equation}
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The optimal Ramsey allocation solves 
\begin_inset Formula $\max_{\{c_t,l_t\}_t}W_0(b_{-1})$
\end_inset

 subject to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "rep agent QL seq implementability"

\end_inset

, feasibility 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "feasibility"

\end_inset

, market clearing for bonds 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "market clearing for bonds"

\end_inset

 and natural debt limit for the government 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{B}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed


\begin_layout Standard
These will be explicitly derived for the cases we solve in this section. We also impose an upper bound 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{B}$
\end_inset

 on government assets.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main results are organized in Theorems 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm: rep agent general theorem"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm: rep agent linear policies"

\end_inset

. The first result obtains some general properties about the invariant distribution of debt for a large class of payoffs. The second result uses a novel expansion method to get an approximation to the mean and variance of the invariant distribution of debt when payoffs are close the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}^*$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When payoffs are not perfectly aligned, the support of the invariant distribution of debt is wide in the sense that (almost surely) the paths of debt sequences approach any arbitrary lower and upper bounds. Note that tax rates are increasing in debt and the variation in debt is analogously reflected in variation in tax rates. This can be contrasted with both, a complete market benchmark as in Lucas Stokey (1983) where both debt and tax rates will be constant sequences and AMSS (2002) which allows for non-negative transfers and risk-free debt where assets approach the first best and limiting tax rates are zero under these preferences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With some more structure on the payoffs, we show that there is an average inward drift to government assets. More precisely, the multiplier on the implementability constraint is sub (or super) martingale in the region with low (or high) debt. The envelope theorem links the dynamics of the multiplier to that of debts and in turn the concavity of the value function implies mean reversion for debt. This is particularly stark when 
\begin_inset Formula $P(s)\in \mathcal{P}^*(s)$
\end_inset

 where debt converges to a constant. 
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed


\begin_layout Standard
Thus the limiting allocation is a particular Lucas Stokey (1983) with stationary debt and taxes, however the level and sign of the long run debt is determined by the joint properties of shocks and payoffs rather than initial condition as would be the case in Lucas Stokey(1983) 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next to gain more insights about the invariant distribution we linearize the law of motion for the evolution of debt with respect to both the endogenous state variable that is debt today and payoffs. The point of approximation is the closest (in 
\begin_inset Formula $l_2$
\end_inset

 sense) complete market economy corresponding to the steady state of some 
\begin_inset Formula $P(s)\in\mathcal{P}^*(s)$
\end_inset

. Exploiting the structure of these approximate laws of motion allows us to obtain bounds on the standard deviation of debt and also rates at which the mean debt level converges that can be expressed in terms of primitive: shocks and payoffs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm: rep agent general theorem"

\end_inset

 In the representative agent economy satisfying assumptions 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "ass iid"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "ass quasilinear"

\end_inset

, the long run assets under the optimal Ramsey allocation are characterized as follows 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $P\not \in \mathcal{P}^*$
\end_inset

, there is an invariant distribution of government such that
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \[\forall \epsilon>0, \quad \Pr\{B_t<\underline{B}+\epsilon \text{ and } B_t>\overline{B}-\epsilon \quad i.o \}=1\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $P(s)-P(s')>\beta \frac{g(s)-g(s')}{\underline{B}} \quad \forall s,s'$
\end_inset

, then for large enough assets (or debt) there is a drift towards the interior region. In particular the value function 
\begin_inset Formula $V(B)$
\end_inset

 is strictly concave and there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $B_1<B_2$
\end_inset

 such that
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \[\mathbb{E}V'(B(s))>V'(B\_) \quad B\_>B_2 \]
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula \[\mathbb{E}V'(B(s))<V'(B\_) \quad B\_<B_1 \]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $P(s)\in \mathcal{P}^*$
\end_inset

, then the long run assets converge to a degenerate steady state
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \[\lim_tB_t=  B^*\quad a.s \quad \forall B_{-1} \]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $P(s)\in\mathcal{P}^*$
\end_inset

, we can express the long run assets 
\begin_inset Formula \[B^*=\beta \frac{\var(g(s))}{\cov(P(s),g(s))}\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Keeping tax rates (and hence tax revenues in this case) the government needs to finance a higher primary deficit when it gets positive expenditure shock. If in such states the assets pays off more, then optimally the government holds positive assets and uses the these high returns to finance this deficit. On the other hand if payoff are lower in times when the government needs resources, holding debt is valuable since it lowers the interest burden. Thus using the level of its assets 
\begin_inset Formula $B^*$
\end_inset

 it can perfectly span the fluctuations in deficits and the sign is given by the sign of the covariance of 
\begin_inset Formula $P(s)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g(s)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The long run tax rate is inversely related to 
\begin_inset Formula $B^*$
\end_inset

 with the following limits,
\begin_inset Formula \[\lim_{B^*\to\underline{B}}\tau^*=\frac{\gamma}{1+\gamma}\quad \lim_{B^*\to\infty}\tau^*=-\infty\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we proceed to obtain a sharper characterization of the invariant distribution. In general, there is no closed form solution for law of motion of government debt and hence we resort to an approximation. We begin with a orthogonal decomposition for an arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $P(s)$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \[P(s)=\hat{P}(s)+P^*(s)\]
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $P^*(s)\in \mathcal{P}^*$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}(s)$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $g(s)$
\end_inset

. Expanding the policy rules around the steady state of the 
\begin_inset Formula $P^*(s)$
\end_inset

 economy we have the next theorem.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed


\begin_layout Standard
 Formally 
\begin_inset Formula $P^*(s) $
\end_inset

 is obtained by projecting 
\begin_inset Formula $P(s)$
\end_inset

 on the space spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}^*$
\end_inset

. These approximations differ from those obtained in Woodford (XXX) where the point of approximation is a deterministic steady state. Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference ""

\end_inset

 contains more details of the approximation method including comparing outcomes to those obtained numerically solving the same economy.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm: rep agent linear policies"

\end_inset

 The ergodic distribution of debt (using the first order approximation of dynamics near 
\begin_inset Formula $P^*(s)$
\end_inset

 ) has the following properties, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Mean:
\series default
 The ergodic mean is 
\begin_inset Formula $B^*$
\end_inset

 which corresponds to the steady state level of debt of an economy with payoff vector 
\begin_inset Formula $P^*(s)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Variance:
\series default
 The coefficient of variation is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
    \frac{\sigma(B)}{\mathbb E(B)} = \sqrt\frac{\var(P(s)) - |\cov(g(s),P(s))|}{(1+|\cov(g(s),P(s))|)|\cov(g(s),P(s))|}\leq\sqrt\frac{\var(\hat{P}(s))}{\var(P^*(s))}
  \]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Convergence rate:
\series default
 The speed of convergence to the ergodic distribution described by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
    \frac{\EE_{t-1}(B_t-B^*)}{(B_{t-1} - B^*)} = \frac1{1+|\cov(P(s),g(s))|}
  \]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Notice that when payoffs are equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $P^*(s)$
\end_inset

, the government can keep taxes constant and perfectly offset the fluctuations in its surplus with returns 
\begin_inset Formula $P^*(s)B^*$
\end_inset

. Away from this, the incompleteness of markets is binding and shocks are hedged with a combination of changes in tax rates and debt levels. These theorem shows exactly how the deviations from perfect spanning map into larger variances for debt (and taxes) in the long run. Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: ergodic distribution ql"

\end_inset

 shows how the ergodic distribution of debt and taxes spread as we vary the covariance 
\begin_inset Formula $P(s)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g(s)$
\end_inset

. 
\begin_inset Float figure
placement htp
wide false
sideways false
status open


\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Graphics 
	filename plots/ErgodicQL.pdf
	width 7in

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Standard
Ergodic distribution for debt and taxes in the representative agent quasilinear economy for three choices 
\begin_inset Formula $P(s)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: ergodic distribution ql"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Heterogeneous agents
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Sec: het agent"

\end_inset

 In this section we turn to general problem of characterizing outcomes in an economy with heterogeneous agents and transfers. In particular we introduce a second agent who has zero productivity and impose a non negativity constraint on his consumption. Given the Ricardian equivalnce result discussed in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Sec: ricardian eq"

\end_inset

, we maintain a normalization that assets of the unproductive agent are zero throughout this section. 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{assumption}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The productivity of agents are ordered, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_1>\theta_2=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2,t}\geq 0.$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{assumption}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Before we discuss the results, a few words on the assumptions are pertinent. The assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_2=0$
\end_inset

 makes the problem tractable and allows us to obtain a complete characterization of the problem as we wary the Pareto weights. The restriction on consumption is necessary to add curvature to the problem. In more general settings risk aversion will impose Inada restrictions that play a similar role. We now state the theorem and then discuss its implications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega,n$
\end_inset

 be the Pareto weight and mass of the productive agent with 
\begin_inset Formula $n<\frac{\gamma}{1+\gamma}$
\end_inset

. The optimal tax, transfer and asset policies 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\tau_t,T_t,B_t\}$
\end_inset

 are characterized as follows,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\geq n \left(\frac{1+\gamma}{\gamma}\right)$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $T_t=0$
\end_inset

 and the optimal policy is same as in a representative agent economy studied in Theorems 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm: rep agent general theorem"

\end_inset

,and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm: rep agent linear policies"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega< n \left(\frac{1+\gamma}{\gamma}\right)$
\end_inset

, suppose we further assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\min_{s}\{P(s)\}>\beta$
\end_inset

. We have two parts:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
There exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}(\omega)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^*(\omega)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}'(\omega)>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{\omega\to 0}\mathcal{B}(\omega)<0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\begin_inset Formula $B\_>\mathcal{B(\omega)}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[T_t>0, \quad \tau_t=\tau^*(\omega), \textit{ and } B_t=B\_ \quad \forall t\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\begin_inset Formula $B\_\leq \mathcal{B(\omega)}$
\end_inset

, the policies depend on the structure of 
\begin_inset Formula $P(s)$
\end_inset

. 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $P(s)\not \in \mathcal{P}^*$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \[\lim_t T_t>0 \text{ i.o.},\quad \lim_t\tau_t=\tau^*(\omega) \text{ and } \lim_tB_t=\mathcal{B}(\omega)\quad \textit{a.s}\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $P(s)\in \mathcal{P}^*$
\end_inset

we have two cases depending on 
\begin_inset Formula $B\_$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $B\_\leq B^*$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[T_t = 0, \quad \lim_t \tau_t=\tau^{**} (\omega), \textit{ and } \lim_tB_t=  B^*\quad a.s \]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}(\omega)>B\_>B^*$
\end_inset

 
\size small

\begin_inset Formula \[\Pr\{\lim_t T_t = 0, \lim_t \tau_t=\tau^{**}(\omega),\lim_tB_t=  B^* \textit{ or } \lim_t T_t>0 \text{ i.o.},\lim_t\tau_t=\tau^*(\omega), \lim_tB_t=\mathcal{B}(\omega) \}>0 \]
\end_inset


\size normal

\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main concern in this setting with heterogeneous agents is that costs of fluctuating transfers to hedge aggregate shocks are endogenous. The simplifications in the environment allow us to highlight how these depend on the Pareto weights (relative to the mass ) of the Planner: 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\omega,1-\omega\}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to Agents 1 and 2 respectively. A regressive planner who cares a lot about the productive agents in effect faces high costs of using transfers. For such a planner (with a high 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

), increasing transfers also means giving resources to the unproductive agent whose consumption he does not value as much. In fact the threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\omega}=n\left(\frac{1+\gamma}{\gamma}\right)$
\end_inset

 is such that above this, transfers are never used and thus the allocations are identical to the representative agent economy studied before.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a less regressive planner (such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega<\bar{\omega})$
\end_inset

 transfers are an important tool for redistributing resources to the unproductive agent in adverse times. To finance these these it taxes the productive agent and does not need to accumulates a large buffer stock of assets. Thus limiting assets are lower and tax rates are larger for more redistributive planners.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
More general economies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Sec: more general economies"

\end_inset

 The analysis in the previous section was simplified in many dimensions - no curvature on the utility from consumption, lack of persistence in shocks and restricting heterogeneity to two agents. The key implication we could thereby exploit was that the return on debt was exogenous, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{-1}P(s)$
\end_inset

. Adding curvature makes these returns endogenous even for standard risk free bond with a payoff vector 
\begin_inset Formula $P(s)=1$
\end_inset

. Technically, it requires us to additionally keep track relative marginal utilities to characterize how taxes, debt, and transfers react to shocks. This makes it harder to separate spanning and redistribution concerns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the next section we first show that with risk aversion, exact spanning can occur only if shocks are binary and IID. For instance with CES preferences, the limiting allocation has constant relative consumptions and taxes rates. We show that how similar to the quasilinear case, the co movement of interest rates and exogenous shocks govern the governments' incentives to accumulate assets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the last section we numerically solve for a economy with realistic heterogeneity and more general shocks. Using simulations from this economy we verify the long properties of taxes and debt for economies that differ in spanning and re-distributive preferences of the planner. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Spanning with binary shocks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi \left( s;\bm{x},\bm{\rho },s\_\right) $
\end_inset

 be an optimal law of motion for the state variables for the 
\begin_inset Formula $t\geq1$
\end_inset

 recursive problem, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi \left( s;\bm{x},\bm{\rho },s\_\right) =\left( x^{\prime }\left( s\right) ,\rho ^{\prime
}\left( s\right) \right) $
\end_inset

 solves (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:BM2"

\end_inset

) given state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(
\bm{x},\bm{\rho },s\_\right) .$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{definition}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A steady state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left( \bm{x}^{SS},\bm{\rho} ^{SS}\right) $
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\bm{ x}^{SS},\bm{\rho}
^{SS}\right) =\Psi \left( s;\bm{x}^{SS},\bm{\rho} ^{SS},s_{-}\right) $
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\,s,s\_.$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{definition}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since in this steady state 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_i =U_{c}^{i}(s)/U_{c}^{1}(s)$
\end_inset

 does not depend on the realization of shock 
\begin_inset Formula $s,$
\end_inset

 the ratios of marginal utilities of all agents are constant. The continuation allocation depends only on 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}$
\end_inset

 and not on the history 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{t-1}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
% These outcomes are reminiscent though not quite identical to those in a complete market economy (see Werning
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%2007).
\backslash
footnote{
\backslash
textcolor{blue}{David, I have changed it a bit, do you think it reflects our understanding better. The earlier one sounded too cautionary}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%The steady state allocation is optimal for a 
\backslash
emph{modified} complete market problem where the Planner has to additionally adhere to a specific ratio of pairwise consumption (or ``market weights'' as in Werning(2007). However we note that typically, there does not exist an initial distribution of  assets  and list of Pareto weights for which the optimal allocation with complete markets will 
\backslash
emph{coincide} with the aforementioned stationary allocation with incomplete markets.}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin by noting that a competitive equilibrium fixes an allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $\{c_i(s),l_i(s)\}_{i}$
\end_inset

 given a choice for 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\tau(s), \bm{\rho}(s)\}$
\end_inset

 using equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:BM2_Wages_cons"

\end_inset

), (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:BM2_Res_cons"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:BM2_rhoprime"

\end_inset

). Let us denote 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\tau,\bm{\rho},s)$
\end_inset

 as the value for the planner from the implied allocation using Pareto weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\omega_i\}_i$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula \[U(\tau,\bm{\rho},s)=\sum_{i}\omega_i U^i(s).\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As before define 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_i(\tau,\rho,s)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula \[Z_i(\tau,\bm \rho,s)=U^i_c(s)c_i(s)+U^i_l(s)l_i(s)-\rho_i(s)\left[U^1_c(s)c_1(s)+U^1_l(s)l_1(s)\right].\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
% Note that $
\backslash
sum_{i=2}^{N}Z_i(
\backslash
tau,
\backslash
bm  
\backslash
rho,s)$ is the marginal utility adjusted  primary deficit using the implied allocation.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
% %Next we define $Z(
