\end_inset

For the IID case, the optimal policy solves the following Bellman equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{x}(s^{t-1})=\bm{x},\bm{\rho}(s^{t-1})=\bm{\rho}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
 \label{eq:ss-obj}
 	V(\bm x,\bm \rho) = \max_{\tau(s),\bm \rho'(s),\bm x'(s)}\sum_s \pi(s)\left[ U(\tau(s),\bm \rho'(s),s) + \beta(s) V(\bm x'(s),\bm \rho'(s))\right]
 \end{equation}
\end_inset

subject to the constraints 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
 \label{eq:ss-imp}
 	Z_i(\tau(s),\bm \rho'(s),s) + x'_i(s) = \frac{x_i \beta^{-1}P(s) U^i_c(\tau(s),\bm \rho'(s),s)}{\mathbb{E} U^i_c(\tau,\rho)}\text{   for all  $s,i \geq 2$,}\\
 \end{equation}
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{eq:bondcondtion}
 	\sum_s \pi(s)P(s)U^1_c(\tau(s),\bm \rho'(s),s)(\rho_i'(s)-\rho_i) = 0 \text{  for $i \geq 2.$}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Constraint (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bondcondtion"

\end_inset

) is obtained by rearranging constraint (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:BM2_Bonds_cons"

\end_inset

). It implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(s)$
\end_inset

 is a risk-adjusted martingale. We next check if the first-order necessary conditions are consistent with stationary policies for some (
\begin_inset Formula $\bm x, \bm \rho$
\end_inset

).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed


\begin_layout Standard
Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "apndx: numerical methods"

\end_inset

 discuses the associated second order conditions that ensure these policies are optimal
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lemma-simplified-foc"

\end_inset

 With risk aversion 
\begin_inset Formula $\|S\|=2$
\end_inset

 is necessary for a steady state to exist 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(s)\mu_i(s)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_i$
\end_inset

 be the multipliers on constraints (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ss-imp"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bondcondtion"

\end_inset

). Imposing the restrictions 
\begin_inset Formula $x'_i(s) = x_i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho'_i(s) = \rho_i$
\end_inset

, at a steady state 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mu_i,\lambda_i,x_i,\rho_i\}^{N}_{i=2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\tau(s)\}_s$
\end_inset

 are determined by the following equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sys-steadystate"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{eq:ss.imp.simplified}
  	Z_i(\tau(s),\bm \rho,s) + x_i = \frac{\beta^{-1}P(s)x_i U^i_c(\tau(s),\bm \rho,s)}{\mathbb{E} U^i_c(\tau,\rho)}\text{   for all  $s,i \geq 2$,}\\
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
	U_{\tau}(\tau(s),\bm \rho,s)-\sum_i\mu_i Z_{i,\tau}(\tau(s),\bm \rho,s)  =0 \text{  for all $s$,} \label{eq:foc.tau.simplified}\\
   \end{equation}
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
	U_{\rho_i}(\tau(s),\bm \rho,s) -\sum_j\mu_jZ_{j,\rho_i}(\tau(s),\bm \rho,s)+ \lambda_iP(s)U^1_c(\tau(s),\bm \rho,s)-\lambda_i\beta\mathbb{E}P(s)U^1_c(\tau(s),\bm \rho(s),s) =0. \text{   for all $s,i \geq 2$ }\label{eq:foc.R.simplified}
 \end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the shock 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 can take only two values, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "sys-steadystate"

\end_inset

 is a square system in 
\begin_inset Formula $4(N-1)+2$
\end_inset

 unknowns 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mu^{SS}_i,\lambda^{SS}_i,x^{SS}_i,\rho^{SS}_i\}^{N}_{i=2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\tau^{SS}(s)\}_{s}$
\end_inset

. 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The behavior of the economy in the steady state is similar to the behavior of the complete market economy characterized by Werning (2007). Both taxes and transfers depend only on the current realization of shock 
\begin_inset Formula $s_t$
\end_inset

. Moreover, the arguments of Werning (2007) can be adapted to show that taxes are constant when preferences have a CES form 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{1-\sigma}/(1-\sigma) - l^{1+\gamma}/(1-\gamma) $
\end_inset

 and fluctuations in tax rates are very small when preferences take forms consistent with the existence of balanced growth. We return to this point after we discuss convergence properties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem.1"

\end_inset

 provides a simple way to verify existence of a steady state for wide range of parameter values by checking that there exists a root for system (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sys-steadystate"

\end_inset

). Since the system of equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sys-steadystate"

\end_inset

) is non-linear, existence can generally be verified only numerically. Next, we provide a simple example with risk averse agents in which we can show existence of the root of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sys-steadystate"

\end_inset

) analytically. The analytical characterization of the steady state will help us develop some comparative statics and build a connection from the quasilinear economy to the quantitative analysis to appear in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference ""

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
A two-agent example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: 2 agent example"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider an economy consisting of two types of households with 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta _{1,t}>\theta _{2,t}=0$
\end_inset

. One period utilities are 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln c-\frac{1}{2}l^{2}.$
\end_inset

 The shock 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 takes two values, 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in \left\{
s_{L},s_{H}\right\} $
\end_inset

 with probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr \left( s|s\_\right) $
\end_inset

 that are independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{-}.$
\end_inset

 We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left( s\right) =g$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta _{1}\left( s_{H}\right) >\theta _{1}\left( s_{L}\right) .$
\end_inset

 We allow the discount factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(s)$
\end_inset

 to depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $s.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm long run forces"

\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset

Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $g<\theta (s)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s.$
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R(s)$
\end_inset

 be the gross interest rates and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=U^2_c(s)\left[b_2(s)-b_1(s)\right]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Countercyclical interest rates.
\series default
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $P \left( s_{H}\right) =P\left( s_{L}\right)$
\end_inset

, then there exists a steady state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left( x^{SS},\rho ^{SS}\right) $
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{SS}>0,\ R^{SS}\left( s_{H}\right) <R^{SS}\left( s_{L}\right) .$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Acyclical interest rates.
\series default
 There exists a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ P\left( s_{H}\right) ,P \left( s_{L}\right)
\right\} $
\end_inset

 such that there exists a steady state with 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{SS}>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{SS}\left(
s_{H}\right) =R^{SS}\left( s_{L}\right)$
\end_inset

. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Procyclical interest rates.
\series default
 There exists a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ P \left( s_{H}\right) ,P\left( s_{L}\right)
\right\} $
\end_inset

 such that there exists a steady state with 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{SS}<0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{SS}\left( s_{H}\right) >R^{SS}\left( s_{L}\right) .$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In all cases, taxes 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(s)=\tau^{SS}$
\end_inset

 are independent of the realized state. 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this two-agent case, by normalizing assets of the unproductive agent (using theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "theorem: main"

\end_inset

) we can interpret 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 as the marginal utility adjusted assets of the government. Besides establishing existence, the proposition identifies the importance of cyclical properties of real interest rates in determining the sign of these assets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm long run forces"

\end_inset

 shows two main forces that determine the dynamics of taxes and assets: fluctuations in inequality and fluctuations in the interest rates. Let's start with part 2 of proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm long run forces"

\end_inset

, which turns off the second force. When interest rates are fixed, the government can adjust two instruments in response to an adverse shock (i.e., a fall in 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_1$
\end_inset

): it can either increase the tax rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau $
\end_inset

 or it can decrease transfers 
\begin_inset Formula $T.$
\end_inset

 Both responses are distorting, but for different reasons. Increasing the tax rate increases distortions because the deadweight loss is convex in the tax rate, as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "Barro1979"

\end_inset

. This force operates in our economy just as it does in representative agent economies. But in a heterogeneous agent economy like ours, adjusting transfers 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is also costly. When agents' asset holdings are identical, a decrease in transfers disproportionately affects a low-skilled agent, so his marginal utility falls by more than does the marginal utility of a high-skilled agent. Consequently, a decrease in transfers increases inequality, giving rise to a cost not present in representative agent economies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The government can reduce the costs of inequality distortions by choosing tax rate policies that make the net asset positions of the high-skilled agent decrease over time. That makes the two agents' after-tax and after-interest income become closer, allowing decreases in transfers to have smaller effects on inequality in marginal utilities. If the net asset position of a high-skilled agent is sufficiently low, then a change in transfers has no effect on inequality and all distortions from fluctuations in transfers are eliminated.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed


\begin_layout Standard
This convergence outcome has a similar flavor to "back-loading"
\begin_inset space \space{}

\end_inset

results of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "Ray2002"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "Albanesi2012"

\end_inset

 that reflect the optimality of structuring policies intertemporally eventually to disarm distortions.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
% If consumption is ordered i.e it is higher in booms than in recessions, interest rates are countercyclical. The government will hold positive assets as long as the steady state marginal utility adjusted primary deficit$Z(
\backslash
tau,
\backslash
rho,s)$ is countercyclical too.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
% It is possible to show numerically
\backslash
footnote{Appendix 
\backslash
ref{apndx: numerical methods} describes a numerical test for existence and local stability cast in terms of  primitives.} that the steady state described in part
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
% 2 of  proposition 
\backslash
ref{thm long run forces} is stable, so the  economy converges to it. This convergence outcome has
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
% a similar flavor to "back-loading"
\backslash
 results  of
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
% 
\backslash
cite{Ray2002} and 
\backslash
cite{Albanesi2012} that reflect the  optimality of structuring policies intertemporally eventually to disarm  distortions.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
% Theorem 
\backslash
ref{theorem: main} provides  a useful way to compare our results with
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%  representative agent economies. By that theorem, we can normalize $%
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
% b_{2,t}=0 $ for all $t$, in which case the negative of net assets of high-skilled agents can be
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
% interpreted as assets of the government. Because $x^{SS}>0,$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
% the government  accumulates assets over time$,$ as in  AMSS.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Turning now to the second force, interest rates generally fluctuate with shocks. Parts 1 and 3 of proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm long run forces"

\end_inset

 indicate what drives those fluctuations. This is the same force that was operating in the representative agent quasilinear economy studied in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Sec: quasilinear"

\end_inset

. Exploiting linearity allowed us to get sufficient conditions for existence of steady state and provide a sharper characterization of how co-movement of interest rates matter. Here in the case with binary shocks we can sign the debt as flip the ordering of interest rates by changing the gap 
\begin_inset Formula $P(s_L)-P(s_H)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Stability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we extend the approximation methods used to characterize outcomes in Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm: rep agent linear policies"

\end_inset

 to the general problem with risk aversion. Instead of obtaining an analytical characterization as in the quasilinear case, we present a test for convergence show local stability of a steady state for a wide range of parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As before, let assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(s)\mu_i(s)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_i$
\end_inset

 be the multipliers on constraints (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ss-imp"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bondcondtion"

\end_inset

). In Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "apndx: numerical methods"

\end_inset

 we show that the history-dependent optimal policies (they are sequences of functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $s^t$
\end_inset

) can be represented recursively in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\bm \mu(s^{t-1}),\bm \rho(s^{t-1})\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_t$
\end_inset

. A recursive representation of an optimal policy can be linearized around the steady state using 
\begin_inset Formula $(\bm{\mu},\bm{\rho})$
\end_inset

 as state variables.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed


\begin_layout Standard
One could in principle look for a solution in state variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\bm{x}(s^{t-1}),\bm{\rho}(s^{t-1})\right)$
\end_inset

. For 
\begin_inset Formula $I=2$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\theta_i(s)\}$
\end_inset

 different across agents, this would give identical policies and a map which is (locally) invertible between 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\mu}$
\end_inset

 for a given 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\rho}$
\end_inset

. However in other cases, it turns out there are unique linear policies in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\
bm{\mu},\bm{\rho}
)$
\end_inset

 and not necessarily in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\bm{x},\bm{\rho})$
\end_inset

. This comes from the fact that the set of feasible 
\begin_inset Formula $(\bm{x},\bm{\rho})$
\end_inset

 are restricted at time 0 and may not contain an open set around the steady state values. When we linearize using 
\begin_inset Formula $(\bm{\mu},\bm{\rho})$
\end_inset

 as state variables, the optimal policies for 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{x}(s^t),\bm{\rho}(s^t)$
\end_inset

 converge to their steady state levels for all perturbations in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\bm{\mu},\bm{\rho})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formally, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Psi}_{t}= \left[\bmat \bm{\mu}_{t} - \bm{\mu}^{SS}\\ \bm \rho_t - \bm \rho^{SS}\emat\right]$
\end_inset

 be deviations from a steady state. From a linear approximation, one can obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $B(s)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
 \hat{\Psi}_{t+1}=B(s_{t+1})\hat{\Psi}_t. \label{eq.linear.lom}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

This linearized system has coefficients that are functions of the shock. The next proposition describes a simple numerical test that allows us to determine whether this linear system converges to zero in probability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm: localstability"

\end_inset

 If the (real part) of eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}B(s)$
\end_inset

 are less than 1, system (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq.linear.lom"

\end_inset

) converges to zero in mean. Further for large 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, the conditional variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Psi}$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{\Psi,t}$
\end_inset

, follows a deterministic process governed by 
\begin_inset Formula \[\text{vec}(\Sigma_{\Psi,t})=\hat{B} \text{vec}(\Sigma_{\Psi,t-1}),\]
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 is a square matrix of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $(2I-2)^2$
\end_inset

. In addition, if the (real part) of eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 are less than 1, the system converges in probability. 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The eigenvalues (in particular the largest or the dominant one) are instructive not only for whether the system is locally stable but also how quickly the steady state is reached. In particular, the half-life of convergence to the steady state is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\log(0.5)}{\|\iota\|}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\iota\|$
\end_inset

 is the absolute value of the dominant eigenvalue. Thus, the closer the dominant eigenvalue is to one, the slower is the speed of convergence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We used Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm: localstability"

\end_inset

 to verify local stability of a wide range of examples. Since the parameters space is high dimensional we relegate the comparative statics to Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference ""

\end_inset

. The typical finding is that the steady state is stable and that convergence is slow. The rates of convergence are increasing in the covariance of interest rates and governments needs for revenue.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Numerical example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a last step in this analysis we finally turn to numerical methods and solve for more general economies in economies where a degenerate steady state does not exist. Using simulations we verify the key predictions of the theoretical analysis in the previous sections regarding the properties of ergodic distribution of debt and taxes. We frst briefly discuss the calibration and then move on to the results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Calibration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The heterogeneity is calibrated by using 10 agents that captured the deciles of the US earning distribution with labor productivities given by the following table, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\theta =  [  1.  ,   1.6 ,   2.45,   3.35,   4.4 ,   5.6 ,   7.  ,   8.9 ,
        12.  ,  22.  ]
\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The preference over consumption and labor given by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
	\psi \log(c) + (1-\psi) \log(1-l)
\]
\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 set to be 
\begin_inset Formula $0.6994$
\end_inset

 to capture a Frisch elasticity of 0.5. The discount factor was set at 
\begin_inset Formula $0.98$
\end_inset

 and the level of exogenous government expenditure was assumed to be constant 
\begin_inset Formula $0.206$
\end_inset

 to get a pre-trasnfers expenditure to output ratio of XX. Our baseline case has a risk free bond and utilitarian planner who assigns equal weights to all agents. Aggregate TFP is calibrated to have a mean and standard deviation of 3%.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution method is adapted from Evans (2014) and described more in the Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference ""

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Wide support of ergodic distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To verify the wide support of the ergodic distribution we take the initial conditions at the end of the long simulation and subject the economy to a sequence of 120 TFP shocks which are 2 standard deviations below the mean. In figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: wide support of taxes"

\end_inset

 we plot the debt and tax rate during this sequence of bad shocks. 
\begin_inset Float figure
placement htp
wide false
sideways false
status open


\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: wide support of taxes"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Graphics 
	filename plots/widesupport.png
	width 70text%

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Standard
This plots the simulation of tax rates for a sequence of 120 negative (2 s.d below the mean) TFP shocks
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We see that given a sufficiently long sequence of bad shocks the economy will eventually deviate significantly from its ergodic mean.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Convergence Speed
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We next check how the speed of convergence to the ergodic mean varies as we change the correlation of payoffs with the exogenous shock. For this we depart from the baseline risk free bond economy to the payoff structure which pays off more in high TFP states. In particular 
\begin_inset Formula \[
	P_t = 1. + 0.5\epsilon_t
\]
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 is the TFP shock. Since marginal utilities are countercyclical, this reduces the correlation of the payoff, 
\begin_inset Formula $U^i_{c,t}P_t$
\end_inset

, with the aggregate shock. In figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: convergence speed"

\end_inset

 we plot a sample path of aggregate marginal utility adjusted debt and the ratio of marginal utilities of the lowest productivity agent to the highest productivity agent for the baseline case (blue) and the modified payoff structure case (green). Both economies start out at the same initial distribution of Pareto weights and multipliers on the implementability constraint and received the same sequence of aggregate shocks. We see that the economy with the lower correlation of payoff with aggregate shock converges to the steady state at a much slower rate. 
\begin_inset Float figure
placement htp
wide false
sideways false
status open


\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: convergence speed"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Graphics 
	filename plots/convergence.pdf
	width 70text%

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Standard
Long sample path for ratio of marginal utilities of Agent 10 to Agent 1 for the bond economy (blue) and the economy with smaller correlation of interest rates and TFP(green).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Cyclicality of interest rates and sign of government assets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We generate procyclical interest rates by transforming the payoffs as follows 
\begin_inset Formula \[
	P_t = 1. + 1.5\epsilon_t
\]
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 is the TFP shock.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We then plot the a long simulation of debt and taxes in the bond economy and the economy with modified payoffs that gives us procyclical interest rates i n figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: debt"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Float figure
placement htp
wide false
sideways false
status open


\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: debt"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Graphics 
	filename plots/long_simulation_deb_taxes.png
	width 70text%

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Standard
Long sample path for government assets and taxes for the bond economy (black) i.e countercyclical interest rates and the economy with procyclical interest rates (red).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Government assets and re-distributive concerns:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our final conclusion was that the assets held by the government in the steady state was decreasing in the redistributive motive of the government. We check this last part by changing the Pareto weights of the government. In our baseline case the government places equal Pareto weights on all agents. We introduce a redistributive motive through a parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

. The planner places evenly spaced Pareto weights from 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1-\alpha$
\end_inset

 on the lowest productivity agent to 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1+\alpha$
\end_inset

 on the highest productivity agent. 
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed


\begin_layout Standard
For example when 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha = 0.025$
\end_inset

 the vector of Pareto weights will be 
\begin_inset Formula \[
[ 0.075     ,  0.081  0.086,  0.092,  0.097,
        0.103  0.108  0.114,  0.119 , 0.125     ]
\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As alpha increases the redistributive motive decreases. We plot total assets of the government in steady state as a function of alpha in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: comp_statics"

\end_inset

 and see that the relationship does indeed hold. 
\begin_inset Float figure
placement htp
wide false
sideways false
status open


\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: comp_statics"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
