\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $I=2$
\end_inset

, proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm long run forces"

\end_inset

 signs the marginal utility adjusted net assets that we denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

. This implies a particular ordering of net assets across the agents in the steady state. These implications generalize to settings with 
\begin_inset Formula $I\geq3$
\end_inset

 and more general shocks. In general, one can verify in the baseline with a risk free bond(as in part 1 of proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm long run forces"

\end_inset

 when interest rates are countercyclical), mean long run net asset levels (scaled by marginal utilities) are ordered inversely to productivities. By making net asset positions be negatively correlated with labor earnings, the planner can minimize the costs of fluctuating transfers over time.
\end_layout

